definition.value: A ketoaldonic acid phosphate that is the 6-phospho derivative of 2-dehydro-D-gluconic acid.
Dicarboxylic acids formed from aldoses by replacement of both terminal groups (CHO and CH2OH) by carboxy groups.
Any carbohydrate acid formed by oxidising the aldehyde functional group of an aldose to a carboxylic acid functional group. Aldonic acids have the general formula HOCH2[CH(OH)]nC(=O)OH.

Any of the naturally occurring, basic nitrogen compounds (mostly heterocyclic) occurring mostly in the plant kingdom, but also found in bacteria, fungi, and animals. By extension, certain neutral compounds biogenetically related to basic alkaloids are also classed as alkaloids. Amino acids, peptides, proteins, nucleotides, nucleic acids, amino sugars and antibiotics are not normally regarded as alkaloids. Compounds in which the nitrogen is  exocyclic (dopamine, mescaline, serotonin, etc.) are usually classed as amines rather than alkaloids.
Any amine formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by alkyl groups.
A 2-amino-3-methylpentanoic acid having either (2R,3S)- or (2S,3R)-configuration.
An amide of an amino acid formed formally by conversion of the carboxy group to a carboxamido group.
An alcohol containing an amino functional group in addition to the alcohol-defining hydroxy group.
A disaccharide derivative that is a disaccharide having one or more substituted or unsubstituted amino groups in place of hydroxy groups at unspecified positions.
An amino alcohol having two hydroxy functional groups.
Any purine having at least one amino substituent.
Any anhydro sugar formally arising by elimination of water from two hydroxy groups of a single molecule of a hexose or hexose derivative.
Intramolecular ethers formally arising by elimination of water from two hydroxy groups of a single molecule of a monosaccharide (aldose or ketose) or monosaccharide derivative.
Any  aromatic amine that is benzene carrying at least one amino substituent and its substituted derivatives.
A monoatomic or polyatomic species having one or more elementary charges of the electron.
A class of macrocyclic lactams that consist of an aromatic (phenyl or naphthyl) or quinonoid (benzoquinone or naphthoquinone) moiety that is bridged by an aliphatic chain.
A pentitol that is the sugar alcohol produced by the reduction of arabinose or lyxose. It is found in serum or urine of human infected with Candida albicans.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of arginine at the amino group, the carboxy group, or the guanidyl group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of arginine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing arginine residues.
An arsenic oxoanion resulting from the removal of one or more protons from arsenous acid.
Any organoarsenic compound that is the As-organyl derivative of arsonic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid amide in which the amide linkage is bonded directly to an arene ring system.
A ketoaldonate that is the conjugate base of ascorbic acid.
An alpha-amino acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the alpha-carbon of glycine is substituted by a 2-amino-2-oxoethyl group.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of asparagine at the amino group, the carboxy group, or the carboxamide, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of asparagine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing asparagine residues.
An L-alpha-amino acid which is L-aspartic acid or any of the essential amino acids biosynthesised from it (asparagine, lysine, methionine, threonine and isoleucine). A closed class.
An alpha-amino acid that consists of succinic acid bearing a single alpha-amino substituent
Any nitrogen molecular entity containing the group -N3.

Any member of the wide class of molecules that share the core azobenzene structure, comprising two phenyl rings linked by a N=N double bond, which may have different functional groups extending from the rings.
The most used of the bafilomycins, a family of toxic macrolide antibiotics derived from Streptomyces griseus.
